    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-28T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-28T20:00:00-05:00" n="674"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d674">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3–146: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-03-01T08:00:00+07:00"
                            >March 1, 1946—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 1—4:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>396. Situation changed by new exchange regulations promulgated February 25 and
                    going into effect on March 4. (ReEmbtel [<hi rend="italic">Deptel</hi>] 276 of
                    February 13.) Provisions for functioning of appointed banks intended to cover
                    foreign banks. Adler will visit Shanghai next week and report<note n="85"
                        xml:id="d674fn85">Apparently no report was sent.</note> on how regulations
                    are working out with respect to American banks and whether any further action
                    necessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
